<p>
An equation where both differential and integral operators will appear in the same equation is called <b>integro–differential equation</b>.
</p>

<p>
Integro–differential equations might be used in the science. Such as heat transfer, diffusion process, neutron diffusion and biological species coexisting together with increasing and decreasing rates of generating.
</p>

<p>
In the integro-differential equations, it is important to note that the unknown function \( u(x) \) and one or more of it is derivatives such as \( u^{\prime}(x), u^{\prime \prime}(x), \dots \) appear out and under the integral sign as well. One quick source of integro – differential equations can be seen when we convert a Differential Equation to an Integral Equation using Leibnitz rule.
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
<span class="l-example">
\( u^{\prime}(x)=x-\int_{0}^{1} e^{x-t} u(t) d t, u(0)=0 \)
</span>
</td>
<td>
(4.1)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
<span class="l-example">
\( u^{\prime \prime}(x)=e^{x}-x+\int_{0}^{1} x t u^{\prime}(t) d t, u(0)=1, u^{\prime}(0)=1 \)
</span>
</td>
<td>
(4.2)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
