</span>
</td>
<td>
(4.4)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
To determine solution of an integro-differential equation, the initial conditions should be given, and this may be clearly seen as a result of involving \( u(x) \) and its derivatives. Initial conditions are needed to determine the constants of integration. In this section we are going to discuss the reliable methods to solve Fredholm integro-differential equations and focus on the equations that involve separable Kernels where Kernel \( K(x, t) \) can be expressed as a finite sum of the form;
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
<span class="l-example">
\( K(x, t)=\sum_{k=1}^{n} g_{k}(x) h_{k}(t) \)
</span>
</td>
<td>
(4.5)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Without loss of generality, we are going to make our examination on a term Kernel \(K(x, t)\) of the form
</p>

<p>
<table class="formula">
<td>
<span class="l-example">
\( K(x, t)=g(x) h(t) \)
</span>
</td>
<td>
(4.6)
</td>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The non-separable Kernel can be reduced to separable Kernel by using Taylor expansion for the Kernel involved.
</p>